# Authentication Examples for REST Client
# This file demonstrates various authentication methods supported by the extension

### Basic Authentication - Using Header
# Standard Basic authentication with username and password
GET https://httpbin.org/basic-auth/user/passwd
Authorization: Basic dXNlcjpwYXNzd2Q=

### Basic Authentication - Using Comment Directive
# Alternative syntax using @basic comment directive
# @basic user passwd
GET https://httpbin.org/basic-auth/user/passwd

### Basic Authentication - With Variables
# Using environment variables for credentials
# Configure these in .http-client-env.json:
# {
#   "dev": {
#     "username": "{{$processEnv API_USER}}",
#     "password": "{{$processEnv API_PASSWORD}}"
#   }
# }
# @basic {{username}} {{password}}
GET https://httpbin.org/basic-auth/myuser/mypass

### Bearer Token Authentication - Using Header
# Standard Bearer token authentication
GET https://httpbin.org/bearer
Authorization: Bearer mySecretToken123

### Bearer Token Authentication - Using Comment Directive
# Alternative syntax using @bearer comment directive
# @bearer mySecretToken123
GET https://httpbin.org/bearer

### Bearer Token Authentication - With Variables
# Using environment variables for tokens
# Configure in .http-client-env.json:
# {
#   "dev": {
#     "apiToken": "{{$processEnv API_TOKEN}}"
#   }
# }
GET https://httpbin.org/bearer
Authorization: Bearer {{apiToken}}

### JWT Token Authentication
# Bearer authentication with JWT token
# @bearer eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJzdWIiOiIxMjM0NTY3ODkwIiwibmFtZSI6IkpvaG4gRG9lIiwiaWF0IjoxNTE2MjM5MDIyfQ.SflKxwRJSMeKKF2QT4fwpMeJf36POk6yJV_adQssw5c
GET https://api.example.com/protected/resource

### Basic Auth with Special Characters
# Demonstrates handling of special characters in credentials
# Username: user@example.com
# Password: p@ss:w0rd!
GET https://httpbin.org/basic-auth/user@example.com/p@ss:w0rd!
Authorization: Basic dXNlckBleGFtcGxlLmNvbTpwQHNzOncwcmQh

### POST Request with Authentication
# Authentication works with any HTTP method
POST https://httpbin.org/post
Authorization: Bearer mytoken123
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "name": "John Doe",
  "email": "john@example.com"
}

### Multiple Headers with Authentication
# Authentication header works alongside other headers
GET https://httpbin.org/headers
Authorization: Bearer abc123
Accept: application/json
User-Agent: REST-Client/1.0
X-Custom-Header: custom-value

### Environment-Specific Authentication
# Switch between dev/staging/prod environments
# Each environment can have different credentials
# Use "rest-client: switch environment" command to change

# Development environment
# @bearer {{devToken}}
GET https://dev-api.example.com/users

###

# Production environment
# @bearer {{prodToken}}
GET https://api.example.com/users

### Security Best Practices
# IMPORTANT: Never commit real credentials to version control!
#
# Recommended approaches:
# 1. Use environment variables: {{$processEnv API_KEY}}
# 2. Use .http-client-env.json (add to .gitignore)
# 3. Use variables that reference process environment
#
# Example .http-client-env.json:
# {
#   "dev": {
#     "apiToken": "{{$processEnv DEV_API_TOKEN}}",
#     "username": "{{$processEnv DEV_USERNAME}}",
#     "password": "{{$processEnv DEV_PASSWORD}}"
#   },
#   "production": {
#     "apiToken": "{{$processEnv PROD_API_TOKEN}}",
#     "username": "{{$processEnv PROD_USERNAME}}",
#     "password": "{{$processEnv PROD_PASSWORD}}"
#   }
# }
